        <header style="border-bottom: 3px solid #007bff; margin-bottom: 30px; padding-bottom: 10px;">
            <h1 style="color: #007bff; margin: 0;">EducaTech: Hyperlink Guide</h1>
            <p style="font-style: italic; color: #666;">Mastering the bridges of the World Wide Web</p>
        </header>

        <section style="margin-bottom: 30px;">
            <h2 style="color: #2c3e50;">What are Hyperlinks?</h2>
            <p>A <strong>hyperlink</strong> is the digital bridge that connects one web page to another. The <strong>anchor tag</strong> (<code>&lt;a&gt;</code>) is the tool that transforms a static document into an interactive part of the World Wide Web.</p>
        </section>

        <section style="background-color: #eef2f7; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 30px;">
            <h2 style="color: #2c3e50;">The href Attribute</h2>
            <p>The <strong>href</strong> attribute stands for <em>Hypertext Reference</em>. It tells the browser exactly where to go when the user clicks the link, whether it is a website, file, email, or a specific spot on the same page.</p>
            
            <div style="display: flex; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
                <div style="flex: 1; background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; border-left: 5px solid #007bff;">
                    <strong style="display: block; color: #007bff;">Absolute URL</strong>
                    Used for external sites. Requires a protocol (http:// or https://).<br>
                    <code style="background: #eee; padding: 2px 5px;">href="https://www.wikipedia.org"</code>
                </div>
                <div style="flex: 1; background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; border-left: 5px solid #28a745;">
                    <strong style="display: block; color: #28a745;">Relative URL</strong>
                    Used to link to pages on your own website.<br>
                    <code style="background: #eee; padding: 2px 5px;">href="contact.html"</code>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section style="margin-bottom: 30px;">
            <h2 style="color: #2c3e50;">The Target Attribute</h2>
            <p>This optional addition tells the browser <strong>where</strong> to open the linked document.</p>
            <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 10px;">
                <thead>
                    <tr style="background-color: #2c3e50; color: white;">
                        <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: left;">Value</th>
                        <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: left;">Behavior</th>
                        <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: left;">Use Case</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>_self</code></td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Opens in the same tab/window.</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Default for internal site navigation.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>_blank</code></td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Opens in a new tab/window.</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Used for external links.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>_parent</code></td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Opens in the parent frame.</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Used with Frames or iframes.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>_top</code></td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Opens in the full body of the window.</td>
                        <td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Breaks out of all frames.</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </section>

        <div style="border-left: 5px solid #ffc107; background: #fff9e6; padding: 20px; border-radius: 5px;">
            <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #856404;">Pro-Tip: Pseudo-classes</h3>
            <p>Links have "states" based on user interaction. Remember the <strong>LVHA</strong> mnemonic: <strong>L</strong>ink, <strong>V</strong>isited, <strong>H</strong>over, <strong>A</strong>ctive.</p>
            <ul style="list-style-type: none; padding: 0;">
                <li>üîò <code>a:link</code> - Default, unvisited state.</li>
                <li>‚úîÔ∏è <code>a:visited</code> - Link already clicked.</li>
                <li>üñ±Ô∏è <code>a:hover</code> - Mouse pointer is over the link.</li>
                <li>‚ö° <code>a:active</code> - The moment the link is clicked.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

